<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38213e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38213e">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38213e"> 213(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> catechumen</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">And joy is the prevailing expression on the not very expressive faces of the rest of the congregation. They sit on the mud floor, men on the north side and women on the south, also facing west. By the west door a basin has been placed on a three-legged stool, and beside this improvised font is an English missionary reading the baptismal service in the vernacular, Malayalam. By him stands the teacher, who for some months, and indeed years, has been preparing these <mark>catechumens</mark> for this moment. <small> Rev W.S. Hunt, <a name="WSHI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WSHI"><cite title="source">India's Outcastes: A New Era</cite></a> (1924) 1-2</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Catechumen: A new convert under instruction before baptism. Used in reference to the ancient church and in modern missionary churches. Sometimes applied to young Christians generally, and especially to those preparing for the rite of confirmation (OED).  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c08040i" href="c8all.htm#c08040i">VI.C.08:040(i)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
